const faqItems = [
  {
    q: "Why is Ethiopian coffee considered special?",
    a: "Ethiopia is the genetic birthplace of arabica coffee. Wild coffee plants have grown in its highland forests for centuries before cultivation began. This means Ethiopian coffee has extraordinary genetic diversity, with hundreds of distinct varieties (many still unnamed and uncatalogued) that produce flavor profiles no other country can replicate. Ethiopian coffees from Yirgacheffe, Sidama, and Guji regularly produce some of the most intensely floral, fruity, and complex cups in the world of specialty coffee."
  },
  {
    q: "What is the difference between Yirgacheffe, Sidama, and Guji coffee?",
    a: "All three are growing zones within the broader Gedeo and Oromia regions of southern Ethiopia, and all three can produce exceptional washed and natural coffees. Yirgacheffe is the most famous and tends to cup with the highest-elevation character: intense jasmine and bergamot florals, bright lemon and stone fruit acidity. Sidama/Sidamo is broader geographically and cups with slightly more body and darker fruit. Guji is a newer-named region producing coffees that read similarly to Yirgacheffe in floral quality but with more fruit-forward natural-processed character."
  },
  {
    q: "What is Harrar coffee and how is it different from washed Ethiopian?",
    a: "Harrar (also spelled Harar) is a dry-climate region in eastern Ethiopia that produces naturally-processed coffees with a completely different flavor profile from the washed Yirgacheffes of the south. Harrar naturals are known for their blueberry, dark fruit, and wine-like character: rich, heavy-bodied, and ferment-forward. They are an acquired taste for coffee drinkers accustomed to the clean brightness of washed Yirgacheffe, but one of the most distinctive coffees in the world for buyers who enjoy intense, fruit-driven profiles."
  },
  {
    q: "Should I buy washed or natural Ethiopian coffee?",
    a: "Both are worth experiencing and they taste dramatically different. Washed Ethiopian (especially from Yirgacheffe) is the cleaner, brighter expression: floral, citrus-forward, and often compared to tea in its delicacy. Natural Ethiopian (from Yirgacheffe, Guji, or Harrar) is heavier, fruit-forward, and more complex in a fermented-fruit way. If you have never had Ethiopian coffee before, start washed. If you already know and love it, try a natural from the same region to compare."
  },
  {
    q: "Is Ethiopian coffee high in caffeine?",
    a: "Ethiopian coffees are 100% arabica, and arabica contains less caffeine than robusta. Ethiopian arabica varieties have caffeine content similar to other arabica coffees: roughly 1.2% to 1.5% of the dry weight of the bean, yielding approximately 80 to 120mg per 8-ounce cup depending on brew method and grind. Some heirloom Ethiopian varieties may have slightly higher or lower caffeine than commodity arabica, but the difference is not dramatic."
  }
];

